---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SidebarLayout from '../../components/shared/SidebarLayout.astro';
import Accordion from '../../components/shared/Accordion.astro';

import { surgeryNavItems as navItems } from '../../data/surgeryNavItems';
---

<Layout description="Professional tooth extraction services in Tecumseh, ON. Your surgeon will discuss all alternatives and replacement options to protect your long-term dental health."
  title="Extraction of Routine Teeth - Great Lakes Oral & Maxillofacial Surgery Centre">
  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">{JSON.stringify({ "@context": "https://schema.org", "@graph": [
    { "@type": "MedicalWebPage", "name": "Tooth Extraction", "url": "https://www.greatlakessurgerycentre.com/surgery/tooth-extraction", "description": "Professional tooth extraction services in Tecumseh, Ontario. Your surgeon will discuss all alternatives and replacement options to protect your long-term dental health.", "specialty": "Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery" },
    { "@type": "MedicalProcedure", "name": "Tooth Extraction", "procedureType": "Surgical", "bodyLocation": "Teeth, jaw", "description": "Removal of severely decayed, diseased, poorly positioned, or impacted teeth. The surgeon will always discuss alternatives to extraction and replacement options before proceeding.", "preparation": "Tooth, jawbone, and gums numbed with local anesthetic. Additional anesthesia available if needed.", "indication": "Severely decayed teeth, advanced periodontal disease, broken teeth that cannot be repaired, impacted teeth, preparation for orthodontic treatment." },
    { "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What happens during a tooth extraction?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Your surgeon numbs the tooth, jawbone, and gums with a local anesthetic. During extraction you will feel pressure from the tooth being rocked to widen the socket, but should not feel pain. If you feel pain at any time, the surgeon will stop to make you more comfortable before continuing." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is tooth sectioning during extraction?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Some teeth require sectioning when they are firmly anchored in the socket or the root is curved and the socket cannot expand enough for removal. The tooth is cut into sections and each section is removed one at a time. This is a common and safe procedure." } }
    ]},
    { "@type": "VideoObject", "name": "Tooth Extraction — Great Lakes Oral & Maxillofacial Surgery Centre", "description": "An overview of routine tooth extraction including the extraction process and what to expect at Great Lakes Oral Surgery in Tecumseh, Ontario.", "thumbnailUrl": "https://img.youtube.com/vi/BvGQ4ilPKws/maxresdefault.jpg", "uploadDate": "2020-01-01", "embedUrl": "https://www.youtube.com/embed/BvGQ4ilPKws", "contentUrl": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BvGQ4ilPKws", "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Great Lakes Oral & Maxillofacial Surgery Centre", "url": "https://www.greatlakessurgerycentre.com" } }
  ]})}</script>
  <SidebarLayout title="Our Procedures" navItems={navItems} currentPath={Astro.url.pathname} eyebrow="Surgical Procedures" heroSubtitle="Expert oral and maxillofacial surgical procedures performed with precision and care.">
    <Fragment slot="card-header">
      <h2>Extraction of Routine Teeth</h2>
      <p>You, your Dentist and your surgeon may determine that you need a tooth extraction for any number of reasons. Some teeth are extracted because they are severely decayed; others may have advanced periodontal disease, or have broken in a way that cannot be repaired. Other teeth may need removal because they are poorly positioned in the mouth (such as impacted teeth), or in preparation for orthodontic treatment. The removal of a single tooth can lead to problems related to your chewing ability, problems with your jaw joint, and shifting teeth, which can have a major impact on your dental health. To avoid these complications, in most cases, your surgeon will discuss alternatives to extractions as well as replacement of the extracted tooth.</p>
    </Fragment>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <iframe
        class="w-full max-w-[600px] aspect-video"
        src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/BvGQ4ilPKws"
        title="Extraction of Routine Teeth"
        allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
        allowfullscreen
      ></iframe>
    </div>

    <Accordion title="The Extraction Process">
      At the time of extraction your surgeon will need to numb your tooth,
        jawbone and gums that surround the area with a local anesthetic.
        Additional forms of anesthesia are available, if needed, although they
        may require another appointment. During the extraction process you will
        feel a lot of pressure. This is from the process of firmly rocking the
        tooth in order to widen the socket for removal. You may feel pressure
        during your extractions, but should not feel pain. If you do feel pain
        at any time during the extraction please let us know right away. We will
        stop what we are doing in order to make you more comfortable before
        completing your extraction.
    </Accordion>

    <Accordion title="Sectioning a Tooth">
      Some teeth require sectioning. This is a very common procedure done when
        a tooth is so firmly anchored in its socket or the root is curved and
        the socket can’t expand enough to remove it. The doctor simply cuts the
        tooth into sections then removes each section one at a time.
    </Accordion>
  </SidebarLayout>
</Layout>
